snippet.textDisplay: This is so odd...yesterday I read an article in a psychology magazine about how life seems to move faster the older you get, and how at age 40, considering you live until 80, you lived 75% of your life. The reason for this is you experience a lot of new things when you are young, everything is new, and in time life gets filled with routines, and you measure your past life in memories. Memories of new experiences will always remain so the first years of our lives seem to have lasted forever. To stop life moving so fast we need to try something new more often, which gets more difficult as you age, we cannot live a successful life by often changing partners, friends, jobs, etc., but changing things like taking a different route to work or having lunch at a different sandwich shop can make a small difference. Great subject and video Casey!

snippet.textDisplay: Talking about time moving fast: I remember I started watching you a year or two before you began your daily vlogs. A year after you started vlogging I moved to New York City, and I remember running into you and telling you I just moved here. You gave me a hug and told me how exciting it is & welcomed me. Now, more than 4 years later, I relocated to The Netherlands, my 4 years NYC chapter being a crazy adventure. All in all, this is to say that I've been watching you before you even had your first million, before the vlogs, before 368, and I'm honored to have seen this whole journey. Very grateful that I was able to run into you too :)

snippet.textDisplay: I disagree. Time is relative. When you get used to the known and when you stop learning time goes faster. Your brain doesn’t have to work too hard to do the same tasks. It already knows it’s environment. There’s no wonder. Learn a new language. Travel to a country where people have less than you. Talk to strangers. Ask for help. Go on a bicycle trip for a month. Watch Ted talks / hear podcasts about people who have done all of the above. Time only exists when you want it to. No? Meh maybe not
